\b Develop Theoretical Argument for Presidential Partisan Heuristics\
\

\b0 Both reviewers felt that the original theoretical argument was underdeveloped. To address this concern we have significantly improved the discussion of our presidential partisan heuristics argument (see pages 5-8).\
\
- Our original discussion of Fed Staff forecasters\'92 motivation was unclear. So, we start with the assumption that Fed Staff actually want to create a forecast that is as accurate as possible. This is plausible because they could both have a preference (because of professional socialisation, for example) and/or incentive (because of performance reviews and regular private academic analysis that could provoke FOMC or even Congressional scrutiny). Though we don\'92t have direct evidence for some of these mechanisms, multiple pieces of research have found that Greenbook inflation forecasts are generally more accurate than private sector forecasts or other government forecasts. \
\
In the original version of the paper (and in this version as well, see p. 8) we discuss why a heuristic may not be updated. Primarily, as the extensive literature on heuristics shows they are not \'91conscious\'92 judgments.  As such, and as we document extensively as being a major motivation of the paper, they are not being explicitly examined and therefore have not been adequately updated. If they were being examined and updated, then they wouldn\'92t be pure heuristics, but would be rational expectations. The empirical consequence of them being regularly examined and updated is that presidential partisan errors would decrease or even disappear over time.    \
\
We have also clarified in the discussion that the partisan heuristics theory does not assume that Fed Staff have a particular partisan or even an inflation preference. Instead it makes the argument that they incorrectly intuit the effect presidents from different partisan backgrounds have on inflation.\
\
- Our alternative theories challenge the assumption that Fed Staff forecasts are not driven by partisan or inflation preferences and that they act on these preferences essentially in an information game with FOMC policy makers (who also have partisan and/or inflation preferences). In the partisan preference theory they have both partisan and inflation preferences. In the monetary expectations theory they have a strong price stability preference, but not a partisan preference. Deciding which approach is more plausible is then the focus of our empirical investigations. \
\
