- The reviewer brings up the question of whether or not Greenbook forecasts are independent of what Fed Governors want/think. This is a very good question. It is a question that we directly, though admittedly partially address with our two alternative hypotheses. These hypotheses examine the possibility that Fed Staff either have a preference for a particular party and that they are trying to influence FOMC members\'92 decisions (partisan preferences) or that they have a price stability preferences and anticipate that the FOMC will change their monetary policies around elections and thus adjust their forecasts to counter the impact of this (monetary expectations). We test for both of these possibilities and do not find any evidence to support them.  \
\
There are of course other possibilities. The most straightforward of which the reviewer mentions: the Staff, through discussions with FOMC members align their forecasts with FOMC members\'92 expectations. We have added three paragraphs discussing this possibility (p. 11). Though it is difficult to empirically observe if and to what extent such discussions influence Greenbook forecasts, we have reason to believe that the influence largely runs from the Greenbook to FOMC members, rather than the other way around. The main reason for this is that, as Romer and Romer (2008) found, Greenbook and FOMC members\'92 forecasts (made after seeing the Greenbook) are not the same. FOMC members use the Greenbook as a reference point and then tend to make worse predictions than the Greenbook. \
\
This point helps emphasise the importance of having highly accurate Greenbook forecasts and why studying inaccuracy is so important. FOMC members need very accurate reference points, so as their own expectations aren\'92t even worse, resulting in inappropriate and non-prefered monetary policies.   \
\

\b Beliefs of Fed Staff that Presidents\'92 Policies Differ by Their Party ID\
\

\b0 We do not have direct evidence that Fed Staff believe that presidents of different political parties are different with respect to fiscal policy. However, to substantiate the plausibility of such a claim we examined research, largely motivated by the rational partisan expectations literature, that has shown that people with a variety of backgrounds, including market participants expect that inflation will be higher under Democrats than Republicans. This is also the primary assumption in the political economy literature.\
\
Furthermore, it\'92s important to reiterate out that the heuristic theory is based not on the idea that Fed Staff are \'91conservative\'92, just that they incorrectly intuit the effect of presidents from different partisan backgrounds on inflation. We have tried to clarify this point in the paper.\
